{"page_content": "Because of the way we wrote our reducer, it would handle this combined\ndata correctly. (If we\u2019d written it using len, it would not have.)\nFor Further Exploration\nLike I said, MapReduce feels a lot less popular now than it did\nwhen I wrote the first edition. It\u2019s probably not worth investing a\nton of your time.\nThat said, the most widely used MapReduce system is Hadoop.\nThere are various commercial and noncommercial distributions\nand a huge ecosystem of Hadoop-related tools.\nAmazon.com offers an Elastic MapReduce service that\u2019s probably\neasier than setting up your own cluster.\nHadoop jobs are typically high-latency, which makes them a poor\nchoice for \u201creal-time\u201d analytics. A popular choice for these\nworkloads is Spark, which can be MapReduce-y.", "metadata": {"producer": "calibre (4.6.0) [http://calibre-ebook.com]", "creator": "calibre (4.6.0) [http://calibre-ebook.com]", "creationdate": "2020-01-31T21:58:22+00:00", "source": "D:\\Users\\wpoga\\Documents\\Ebooks\\Antigravity Library\\Data Science from Scratch First Principles with Python by Joel Grus.pdf", "file_path": "D:\\Users\\wpoga\\Documents\\Ebooks\\Antigravity Library\\Data Science from Scratch First Principles with Python by Joel Grus.pdf", "total_pages": 513, "format": "PDF 1.4", "title": "Data Science from Scratch: First Principles with Python", "author": "Joel Grus", "subject": "", "keywords": "", "moddate": "2020-02-01T00:59:10+03:00", "trapped": "", "modDate": "D:20200201005910+03'00'", "creationDate": "D:20200131215822+00'00'", "page": 458}, "type": "Document"}
